"1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1346":"1346","1324":"1324","1246":"1246","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","1277":"1277","about 1277":"circa 1277","22 July 1298":"22 juli 1298","about 1300":"circa 1300","1229":"1229","England":"England","Horsley, Derbyshire, England":"Horsley, Derbyshire, England","Swynnerton, Staffordshire, England":"Swynnerton, Staffordshire, England"},"en":{"Abt 1229–about 1300":"about 1229–about 1300","1229–1300":"1229–1300","1215–Female":"1215–Deceased","1245–1270":"1245–1270","1246–1324":"1246–1324","1277–1346":"1277–1346","1215–1250":"1215–1250","about 1270":"about 1270","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","Abt 1229":"about 1229","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1346":"1346","1324":"1324","1246":"1246","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","1277":"1277","about 1277":"about 1277","22 July 1298":"22 July 1298","about 1300":"about 1300","1229":"1229","England":"England","Horsley, Derbyshire, England":"Horsley, Derbyshire, England","Swynnerton, Staffordshire, England":"Swynnerton, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Peshale","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Cornish: locative name from any of more than two dozen places called Penhale in Cornwall, or from places of similar name in Wales, such as Pennal (Merioneths), or from Penheale in Egloskerry (Cornwall). The Cornish places named Penhale derive from Middle Cornish * <i>pen hal</i> ‘moor’s head, marsh’s head’ ( <i>pen</i> ‘head, top, end; promontory’,  <i>hal</i> ‘moor, marsh’); Pennal (Merioneths) has the same meaning. Penheale derives from Middle Cornish  <i>pen</i> +  <i>hel</i> ‘hall’."],"variants":[{"name":"Penhall","meanings":["Cornish:  see  Penhale  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]},{"name":"Swynnerton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Swinnerton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Swinnerton","meanings":["English: habitational name from Swynnerton in Staffordshire. The etymology of the placename is uncertain. It may derive from Old English <i>swille</i> ‘sloppy mess, swill’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Alternatively, the first element may be <i>swīn</i> ‘swine, hog’, <i>swān</i> ‘herdsman, peasant’, <i>swan</i> ‘swan’, or <i>sumor</i> ‘summer’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":30,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705190,"age":61,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Swynnerton de Peshale was born about 1229, in Swynnerton, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard De Pershale, was 15 and his mother, (Mrs. ) De Pershale, was 16. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Anna De Pershale. He died about 1300, in England, at the age of 73."},"et":{"Abt 1229–about 1300":"umbes 1229–umbes 1300","1229–1300":"1229–1300","1215–Female":"1215–Surnud","1245–1270":"1245–1270","1246–1324":"1246–1324","1277–1346":"1277–1346","1215–1250":"1215–1250","about 1270":"umbes 1270","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","Abt 1229":"umbes 1229","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1346":"1346","1324":"1324","1246":"1246","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","1277":"1277","about 1277":"umbes 1277","22 July 1298":"22. juu